english:
  title: Discourse on the Opening and Perusal of the Great Canon at Yeonbok Temple
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Though the Buddha spoke in a single voice, the Great Canon spans ten thousand scrolls—yet all matters of state press upon me with such urgency that I know not a moment's rest. To fortify the realm, we must surely rely upon the Buddha's grace and protection. Thus have I, together with my ministers, made solemn vows: we have raised the five-tiered pagoda temple, restoring luster to the ancient foundation, and printed a thousand cases of sacred texts, completing this new canon.

    Now that these volumes are enshrined and preserved, let them be opened and read aloud. I invite the assembled monks to recite these lotus teachings, that the sound of the dharma horn may resound through the ten directions, and the fragrance of the precepts may suffuse all three realms. The offerings are complete, the merit shall surely bear fruit.

    Yet know that these resources flow from the people themselves—how could their blessing and fortune rest upon myself alone? May the Buddha's mirror of wisdom shine broadly upon all. May the celestial grace descend equally. Let my ancestors ascend to blissful realms above, and let all beings below find joy. May longevity and prosperity flourish, may the royal household dwell in peace and harmony, ever growing in splendor and grace, that the nation's great blessing may extend eternally.

    So shall we beat swords into plowshares, raise the rites and music of civilization, and lay aside the rod of punishment.
  footnotes:
    - The 'single voice' (一音) refers to the Buddha's teaching that resonates differently to each being according to their capacity.
    - The 'three realms' (三界) in Buddhist cosmology comprise the realm of desire, form, and formlessness.
    - This work was written by Kwon Geun, a prominent Goryeo official and scholar, likely as a dedicatory essay for the restoration or printing of Buddhist scriptures.
